{"questionId":"22784","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The following diagram shows a frame that is made from wire. The total length of wire is&nbsp;equal to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>15</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>cm</mtext></math>. The frame is made up of two identical sectors of a circle that are parallel to&nbsp;each other. The sectors have angle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>θ</mi></math> radians and radius <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo> </mo><mtext>cm</mtext></math>. They are connected by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>cm</mtext></math> lengths of wire perpendicular to the sectors. This is shown in the diagram below.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/f22c73567827680ecb4f015deabc690a4d823791.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Show that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>6</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>15</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>r</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>r</mi><mi>θ</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>12</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>r</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>A1</strong></em> for any reasonable working leading to expected result e,g, factorizing <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi></math>.</p>\n<p><br><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>6</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>θ</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"22784","referenceCode":"21N.1.AHL.TZ0.15a","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Show that r=62+θ.","paper":"1","level":"HL","questionNumber":"a","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","SL 5.6—Stationary points, local max and min","Topic 5—Calculus","SL 5.7—Optimisation","Topic 5—Calculus","AHL 5.9—Differentiating standard functions and derivative rules","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.1—3d space, volume, angles, midpoints","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.7—Radians"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}